\begin{small}
When we want to know a number about a chemical reaction, we add up all of the numbers that show how much heat is given off or used up when each little thing in the reaction is made for the first time. First, we add up those numbers for the original way of making the reactants. Then, when we calculate the numbers for making the products in the same way, we subtract the number for making the thing that's gone ("t") alone. The difference is about the same when we calculate the numbers using a model or when we use a more precise method. The difference between the model and the precise method when making the products is: add up those differences for all of the other little things that are made in the reaction, and then add the specific difference for making the thing that's gone alone with its more precise number.
\end{small}

